      "writtenOn": "2017-05-05T14:05:02Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "The compound operators +\u003d, etc. evaluate the LHS as an rvalue prior to assigning to it, meaning that if you\u0027ve got \"x +\u003d y\" then \"x\" actually shows up in the evaluation list prior to this expression. The \"\u003d\" operator is the only operator which *only* evaluates the LHS as an lvalue, and so (in this case) \"x\" will not show up as having been evaluated and therefore needs to be handled differently.",
